<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-310-260  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 310 260.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>First new language classifier since Roget's Thesaurus. (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Woods, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microlytics Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Inside Information (Computer program) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Software PublishersProduct IntroductionSoftware packagesDictionaries.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FIRST NEW LANGUAGE CLASSIFIER SINCE ROGET'S THESAURUS PITTSFORD, NEW YORK,U.S.A., 1990 MAR 30 (NB) -- Microlytics plans to release a new product calledInside Information, which it touts as a &quot;backwards dictionary&quot; and the firstnew classification system for language since Roget developed the thesaurusmore than a century ago.andM;The Macintosh product is a comprehensive hierarchical dictionary whichorganizes the English language into categories of defined words: nature,science and technology; domestic life; institutions; arts and entertainment;language; and the human condition.andP;  These categories contain 20 subclasses,125 categories and 700 subcategories.andP;  Categories are defined by subjectmatter, such as chemistry, law, or music, or by a common property such ascolors, tools, verbs of motion, and even esoteric categories such as insults.andO;The entire database contains more than 65,000 root word entries.andM;Spokesperson Maria Pignataro tells Newsbytes that a there are four functionsfor the product -- the simplest allows the user to simply type in adefinition, and the computer will display words the definition might define.andO;The product can also be used as a briefing tool to familiarize users withtopics.andM;&quot;As a writing tool, Inside Information is the solution to the blank page,&quot;states company President Mike Weiner.andP;  Students researching a paper,journalists investigating a story, or a sales person writing a new industrypitch can instantly find the words and ideas needed to enliven and givecredibility to a piece of writing, according to the company.andM;The product is based on Word Menu, originally developed by novelist, editor,journalist and screenwriter Stephen Glazier.andP;  In the 1970s, Glazier startedkeeping lists of housing and clothing terms for the settings of hishistorical novels.andP;  The next step was to reorganize the entire Englishlanguage into a natural, categorical structure for everyday use and generalreadership.andP;  Assisted by a research staff and dozens of consultants over thepast six years, Glazier produced the raw database which has become InsideInformation.andM;Inside Information, shipping in May, is currently for the Apple Macintoshcomputer with one megabyte or higher of memory.andP;  The desk accessory will cost$119.andP;  Versions for the IBM PC, Unix, and Windows are being developed.andM;(Wendy Woods/19900330/Press Contact: Bob Lang, Microlytics, 716-248-9150)</TEXT></DOC>